               <msContents>
                  <msItem class="#historica" n="1" xml:id="MS_Bodl_697-item1">
                     <title key="work_12228">Historia Iosephi de bello iudaico et excidio urbis Hierosolymitanae ('Hegesippus')</title>
                     <incipit>uiro usque ad exitum uitę studium</incipit>
                     <note>A fourth-century reworking in Latin of Josephus' Greek <title>De bello Iudaico</title> 
                        (<title>The Jewish War</title>). Carson Bay notes that Ps. Hegesippus 'rescripts the narrative of Josephus' first-century, seven book account into five books 
                     for a late antique Christian audience' (Carson Bay, <title>Biblical Heroes and Classical Culture in Christian Late Antiquity: The Historiography, Exemplarity, 
                     and Anti-Judaism of Pseudo-Hegesippus</title> (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2023)</note>
                     <note>The text begins 'uiro usque ad exitum' at <ref target="https://archive.org/details/iosippihegesippi21jose/page/n5/mode/1up?q=%22uiro+usque%22">1. 1.2</ref>, and ends 
                        at <ref target="http://digiliblt.lett.unipmn.it/xtf/view?docId=dlt000241/dlt000241.xml;chunk.id=d1782e2805;toc.depth=1;toc.id=d1782e2133;brand=default">5.53.1</ref> 'circumuallauit hostis omne mu' in the last chapter, a leaf being lost at each end</note>
                     
                     <note>Fol. 54 has the title 'Historie Egesippi de excidio Iudeorum'</note>
                     
                     <note>Hegesippus may have been a misspelling of ‘Josephus’</note>
                     
                     <note>Cf. Cambridge, University Library MS. <ref target="https://archive.org/details/cu31924063523157/page/370/mode/2up?q=uiro">Dd.9.4</ref> and 
                        M.R. James’s <ref target="https://www.repository.cam.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/1810/321073/M.R.%20James%20Dd.9.4.pdf">unpublished description</ref></note>
                     
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem>
